<section xml:id="lesson-09">
  <title>Lesson 9</title>

  <objectives>
    <ul>
      <li>Graph quadratic functions using vertex, axis of symmetry, and intercepts.</li>
      <li>Determine whether a quadratic function has a maximum or minimum value.</li>
      <li>Identify the maximum or minimum value of a quadratic function and where it occurs.</li>
      <li>Use given characteristics to graph a quadratic function.</li>
      <li>Model and analyze a real-world situation using a quadratic function.</li>
    </ul>
  </objectives>

  <subsection xml:id="l9-graphing">
    <title>Graphing Quadratic Functions</title>

    <exercise xml:id="l9-ex1">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Graph the following functions by finding the vertex, axis of symmetry,
          and intercepts.
        </p>
        <ol marker="a.">
          <li><m>f(x) = -x^2 + 2x + 1</m></li>
          <li><m>f(x) = 2x^2 - 16x + 33</m></li>
          <li><m>f(x) = \frac{1}{2}(x - 3)^2 - 2</m></li>
        </ol>
      </statement>
    </exercise>
  </subsection>

  <subsection xml:id="l9-max-min">
    <title>Maximum and Minimum Values</title>

    <exercise xml:id="l9-ex2">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Without graphing, determine whether the function has a maximum or
          minimum value. Then determine the maximum or minimum value and
          where it occurs.
        </p>
        <ol marker="a.">
          <li><m>f(x) = (x - 6)^2 + 10</m></li>
          <li><m>f(x) = -5x^2 + 30x + 200</m></li>
          <li><m>f(x) = 3x^2 + 4x + 3</m></li>
        </ol>
      </statement>
    </exercise>
  </subsection>

  <subsection xml:id="l9-characteristics">
    <title>Using Given Characteristics</title>

    <exercise xml:id="l9-ex3">
      <statement>
        <p>
          A quadratic function has the characteristics given below.
          Use the axis of symmetry to generate two additional points,
          then use all points to graph the function.
        </p>

        <p>
          Vertex: <m>(3, -4)</m>
        </p>
        <p><m>x</m>-intercept: <m>1</m></p>
        <p><m>y</m>-intercept: <m>5</m></p>
      </statement>
    </exercise>
  </subsection>

  <subsection xml:id="l9-application">
    <title>Application</title>

    <exercise xml:id="l9-ex4">
      <statement>
        <p>
          A baseball is thrown upward at a velocity of <m>72</m> ft/sec.
          If it is released at a point <m>6</m> feet from the ground,
          its distance <m>s</m> in feet from the ground at <m>t</m> seconds
          is given by
          <m>s(t) = -16t^2 + 72t + 6</m>.
        </p>
        <ol marker="a.">
          <li>
            When will the baseball reach its maximum height and how high
            will it go?
          </li>
          <li>How long will it remain in the air?</li>
        </ol>
      </statement>
    </exercise>
  </subsection>

</section>